He had under his arm a file with three new rental contracts for three apartments: his own, the one of his daughter and his son who is serving a sentence.
The deregulation has increased the rent for these three people.
Instead of paying 3500 the son will have to pay from next year for a 2+1 second category apartment 4100 crowns.
“And there’s no hot water and heating works on solid fuel,” he said on his son’s new contract, the man who has the power to sign.
"But I signed it anyway," he explains angryly and half-resigned.
The BytyOKD.cz Citizens' Association, which described the current rental conditions as "immoral and indecent", advises tenants not to sign and wait until December 7, when a notice will be published to explain the method to follow to claim.
But the man reacts to this with a hand gesture.
“One says that, the other says something else” by scratching his eyebrows.
The Ostrava region became the laboratory for deregulation.
After New Year, this is what most apartments in the Czech Republic await whose rents do not match the market price.
Aktualne.cz has therefore decided to personally visit the "laboratory".
