The bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Take a look at the interiors of Gaudi.
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric Saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine and the balconies to open mouths of fish.
This is how it is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house has received the nickname of Bone House from the locals.
Organic shapes, wild colours, unusual use of stones, tile fragments and mosaic, façade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is ypic for the Art Nouveau of Antoni Gaudi.
The front façade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that recall nature and animals.
During a more detailed observation we see geometry, rhythm and precisely thought order.
In the night the façade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced by it.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measurement.
The wood waves the window frames, balustrades, the decorative elements of the doors, the eyeliner and the lamellae.
The Battlo house which stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of a 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first emphasized the demolition of the old building and the construction of another brand new, but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-home house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
Architect Josep Maria Jujol was working with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the façade are born.
For the façade also worked other artists and creators.
The joint work for the Casa Battlo plans began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and the Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
Locals nicknamed the hot house just after its finish because of its organic shapes "the Bone House".
Others, considering the specific mechanism for opening the windows, called it "the house giving".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of St. George the patron of Catalonia.
Other building sculpture elements contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi has thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time,with ventilation fans and typical fireplaces.
Their 45-degree inclination seems strange.
During the creation Gaudi absolutely failed to comply with the construction guidelines of the time and was not allowed to be hampered by them.
At the beginning of the construction he obtained the building permit from the city, knowing, of course, that the data on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the city council was horrified and demanded changes.
For example, municipal council members did not like that the building pillars were intruding on the public sidewalk.
There was never any change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city call Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and in the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented at a jewellery store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one accesses to an independent roof terrace.
All straight angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of space linking.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the lounges and the high company can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with Gaudi's reconstruction has received in addition to new façades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, blue and white glazed tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with the wells of lights.
The two-color game gives maximum light in every floor of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the rays of the sun.
The Casa Battlo house, which was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund, may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and splendid apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to take this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the scope of visits to common areas and the attic including roof terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is really inexpensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entrance price in Gaudi's other buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
