Devices to track people are increasingly demanded by parents who want to monitor their children.
Fear for their child makes more and more people think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can just as well be used to trace the movement of people and help in some cases as for example that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as large as a box of lighters but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka moved a large number of people and they started looking for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We strive to tell everyone that this is not spying, but just another way to reduce the likelihood of another tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of MAcro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting them in a person's bag who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“The majority of people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know for what purposes the "box" is used and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws the attention that if the child does not want to wear something of this kind on him, he will get rid of it.
“Even the smallest can show great creativity when it comes to explicitly getting rid of something when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Cell phones, which can cut themselves like these tracking devices, have already brought parents to long expectations,” Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is very questionable.
"If this is a prepared abduction, the author will do everything possible to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
“Right now, it’s the phone.”
“As soon as the tracking devices develop, they (the criminals) will also look for them because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign.”
"In such cases the criminals will always be ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
She nevertheless admits that such devices can help in an unprepared assault by a paedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, says that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an aggression.
"The apparatus may be configured in such a way that it is in regular emission after a specified period of time."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it still remains the last position of the person concerned."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slid and finds himself in the lying position without moving,” Cech says.
According to him, so-called smart cell phones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after formatting it with a special prosoftware.
The problem with current tracking systems is that they are either a device similar to the ones wear in the size of a light box pendant or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"It will have the advantage that the potential aggressor will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time," he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as tracing cars.
This is a combination of position acquisition systems using GPS (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
