I wish my successor a better year than that we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory has been rapidly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the sense of the objective of the winner Farmet has the worst moments behind him.
The one who came to pick up the prize from Slovansky dum for the first place in the Competition for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which it turned a tooling workshop in Ceska Skalice into a firm with a turnover of 100 million crowns.
“I can say that the award has not only encouraged me and my employees and increased our self-confidence in fighting competition,” said the winner of last year’s competition.
At the beginning of the history of the company Farmet there was a desire to do something useful.
And so when the state proposed to Karel Zdrasky's father to rent the little workshop as compensation after the communists' confiscation of property, he did not hesitate for a long time, refused a career in a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades around his father for the manufacture of plastic baths.
Not long after they began to specialize in plant oil presses.
It became after eighteen years the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even in the non-specialized audience after success obtained in the contest through the media.
“Not only our customers started to really get to know the Farmet brand, but also the foreign partners who started to realize that they were working with a company that achieved the greatest success in their home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year did not pass at Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company's assessment was based on the economic outcomes of 2008 and partly of 2009.
And precisely in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machinery.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect citizens, societies were forced to stop their investment projects and begin to limit their purchases of new materials and technologies.
"We have obviously not escaped this situation."
“Revenues have fallen by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even dismiss it,” says Karel Zdarsky.
