Households will pay an additional 100 crowns monthly for housing.
Households will have to pay a surcharge not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
Families will have to pull from their wallets as much as 100 crowns per month from January onwards.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply, and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be around 100 crowns per annum for households in apartments than is now.
However, all suppliers have lowered electricity prices given the sensitive development to encourage the production of renewable energy, including photovoltaic batteries.
The gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the highest consumption.
We can also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
It is mainly the largest municipalities that plan to increase prices.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay for central heating almost 50 more crowns per month from January onwards, while the families of Liberec will pay more than 1,000 crowns per year.
For the inhabitants of Prague a 9 percent increase is being prepared for water and sanitation in case the city increases infrastructure rents.
If rents do not change, Prague will pay an additional 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest compared to the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are rising 7.4 percent.
Rental prices will rise significantly, for example, in the 450,000 rented apartments starting in January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns in Usti nad Labem almost 2,500 apartments, has decided to increase to 100 percent.
Those who will not agree with the further increase in rents will be brought to court by the company.
Regulated rents paid by people in nearly 300 thousand apartments could increase by 10 percent next year.
