Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, for which the Ministry of Defense exchanged transport aircraft Casa C-295M, took off Tuesday to Seville, Spain, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa-EADS is headquartered.
This is the first time that such aircraft have become owned by someone other than the Czech army.
However, they have been abroad in the course of exercises or demonstration thefts.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were so far in service in the Czech army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three aircraft are single-seat versions of the L-159.
These are currently stationed at Aero Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - the firm Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Ministry of Defense’s press department, the physical departure of Vodochody’s planes is currently unknown.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft planned for exchange have been taken on long-stocked aircraft without causing additional loads or investments for the Ministry of Defense."
"The L-159 T1 two-seaters were exchanged in the state," said Pravo Pejsek.
He said the army would not remain without two-seaters since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aero Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 cars into two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, the second being scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS has committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of certain Alliance countries.
“In the contract it is clearly stated that the one who takes the L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries.”
"It is therefore the case of the one who considers how to achieve this," Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced, some time ago, that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not tender and contacted EADS directly.
The defence management argued that the exchange ensured future export of the L-159 abroad.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aero Vodochody and used only 24, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have judicial implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because the aircraft should have been chosen as part of a European tender and under no circumstances by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa aircraft, the last is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
A longer index than the annular is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have the longer index than the annular are exposed to a lower risk of having prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This can depend on the level of male hormone testosterone.
"Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple prostate cancer risk test, especially for men before 60," said co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at Warwick University.
The finger could thus help determine which men should undergo prostate cancer testing, including by combining with genetic risk or other aggravating factors such as family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index shorter than the annular.
For them as well as for the 19 percent of those with fingers of the same length, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the annular, however, the risk dropped to 33 percent, for men before the age of 60 the risk decrease reached 87 percent.
The length ratio of the two fingers cited - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Unless testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research has shown that it is testosterone that helps in the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said for CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
