According to a briefing by U.S. intelligence services dating from late April 2008, the current reactor, known as the neighboring town, el-Kibar, would be well-suited to produce plutonium, which would make it possible to manufacture atomic weapons.
However, this technique has been in use since the 1950s.
The CIA has shown a presentation video featuring blurred satellite images.
Through computer-assisted animation, it indicated the probable location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the power plant, which represents a miniature copy of the North Korean model of the Yongbyon nuclear plant.
In addition, she presented the photos showing the nearby building, or even the inside of it.
It appears that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped with fuel bars.
Today, more than three years after the Israeli bombing, we have little more information than at the time, and even, over time, the mystery becomes more and more thickened.
Former U.S. President George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was certain that Syria had built an el-Kibar reactor, but had little clues that the country was developing “an active nuclear weapons program.”
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about it and only speak of a “supported reactor”, even if they consider the presentation of the CIA to be “plausible.”
They lack tangible evidence, as well as the IAEA.
Asked how he was ensuring that he was dealing with a nuclear reactor, a senior UN diplomat gave only a laconic response in the summer by stating that the IAEA had “sufficient documents to ask questions.”
The Syrians certainly precipitately removed the rubble of the "unused military building" and proceeded to a methodical flattening of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of IAEA experts led by former Chief Inspector Oli Heinonen discovered traces of human-produced uranium at el-Kibar.
In addition, the IAEA has received satellite images from commercial providers from a member state showing the moment that followed the attack directly, which appears to be more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the anonymous sponsor, perhaps Israel, has acquired them exclusively.
It is therefore impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity objectively.
Syria has always assured that it has never carried out a secret nuclear program and that it has not built a reactor.
Damascus argues that the uranium found on the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA rejected this argument after analyzing the particles, calling it unlikely.
Since then, Damascus has refused any discussion on this, as well as on satellite images.
In addition, Syria does not allow controllers to carry out a second inspection on the site of el-Kibar and refuses access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But even Israel keeps a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister in office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comment on this."
Thus, the investigation into this case has continued since June 2008 without any results and is "becoming increasingly a serious problem of the Agency's credibility", as a senior Western diplomat in service at the IAEA headquarters in Vienna recognizes, ultimately it is a serious violation of the Nuclear Weapons Prohibition Treaty.
