The Democratic Routine
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as does that for private enterprise.
Crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the United States in much of the region.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarómetro survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it follows attitude changes in the region.
Two related elements emerge from the results of this year's poll, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the fairly sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the increasing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a minimum of 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy recovered after a sharp drop in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populated countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Table 2).
Approximately 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with how their country's democracy worked in practice; this is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase over 25 per cent in 2001 (graph 3)
Around 34% said they had confidence in their country's parliament and 45% in their government, the same as last year in both cases; but a sharp increase compared to 2003 (respectively 17% and 24%).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America shaken support for democracy.
While this has remained strong during the global financial crisis, it is certainly due to the fact that many countries in America have only suffered a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a social security network has helped protect the poor.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty increased only slightly in 2009 and again dropped to 32% this year.)
But the mood varies considerably from country to country (see graph 4).
Brazil’s good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, translates into a widely shared sense of progress
This is rarer in Mexico and Central America where the recession has been more severe and violent crimes have worsened.
It is only for the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the biggest problem for their country (see Table 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or their loved ones have been victims of a criminal act in the past year; nevertheless, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
Stronger economic performance is reflected in the rise in support for private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents in the region say that private enterprise is essential for development, compared to 56% in 2007 (see Graph 6).
