Can civility bring gaps closer?
After a campaign marked by invectiveness and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a warning sign of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to the party struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the “lame duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion on the differences between the two sides as well as on the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting on the president’s deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, further divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a period of mutual trial and testing for signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed party war.
That's why Tuesday's meeting and subsequent comments from participants unveiled a minimum of requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether taxation, spending, health care or rights, both sides remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed in the tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now on the side of the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“It is inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions, and then they fade.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "lame duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of them, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment allowances, even because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax reductions for the wealthy, while denying unemployment allowances to unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday's White House meeting, more optimism is planning on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the "lame duck" session, with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily mean a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done will be done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what happens between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present in tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to meet their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early reactions to the deficit committee's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, raising retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, according to themselves, imposed the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, composed of 18 members, to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected members of the group, suggesting that there is little reason or willingness to compromise on tax matters, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the fighting between the White House and Congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans dispute Obama in budget, tax and health care; then followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the supportive spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the public’s reaction.
Those who will be judged in loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would nevertheless be an optimistic view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are bigger today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But much more effort will be needed on both sides to find a ground of understanding on the issues that further divide them.
