On the other hand, Vice-President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, joins the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel regarding her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be noted that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another restriction on the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which shocks with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits from the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, although now it seems science fiction, with a very favorable stream of opinion, nearly 50% of the population.
The third is a new conception of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines to countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments of one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of the potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and it has long been defined, so now there is no room for apology.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission boosted deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany thought should be done (tax rigor plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, were doing.
The second coup of the central European country was when Merkel hardly prolonged the decision to save Greece.
From that moment on she was subjected to fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion and published were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expressed a clear position, calling for the reform of the Treaties of the Union to enable the rescue of a country and at the same time oblige private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the following months, we should attend the reform process of the Union that will make these measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not think it will cross.
And she tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date the old operation of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that violate the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves to cease payments and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a part of the costs.
Germany informs us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that presided over Spanish growth in the years of the boom, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be bad not to hear it.
It is not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked for is much harder.
And what he should absolutely not do in these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give us greater tranquility.
And let us know how to seize the opportunity that we were given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero also heard this in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel's criticism, we have paved the way to the thesis that we need to put order at home.
But the red line that Germany traced is there, and they don’t seem to move it.
And among the possibilities that are being considered, we cannot exclude that of abandoning a monetary zone too full of unserious countries.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had warned us.
Sport and Fraud of the Law
The tricks similar to that of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate the ingenuity but not the willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the November 23 game against Ajax in the Champions League has dropped a lot of ink on the anti-sports character of such behaviour and whether the two players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before the game ended (which their team was already winning clearly), the two players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually become the leader of its group, the two players will carry out the regulatory sanction during the next game of the dam game against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee sanctioned team coach José Mourinho with two matches and different economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, if not rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of ethos, the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the case related is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team of the entity of Real Madrid (who in his hymn displays nobility and honor and who in previous occasions has sentenced a fine to his players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, he seems, by his Mourinho, which adds a more episode of ditech.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of behaviour is not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradict the principles of sport, that is, if with these actions one commits a fraud of law; because, indeed, they are actions that respect the sports regulations, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to consider the type of harm they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the goods that includes sports spirit is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, i.e. there has been no violent play.
Another of these goods to be referred to with the right game is to prevent the team of infringing players from unfairly enjoying the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of Real Madrid players is that it is not comfortable with what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They were waiting and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of advantage that offenders obtain from the intentional mistakes examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put the rival in a disadvantage situation and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action assumes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And it’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club couldn’t count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with some degree of indetermination, as the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players carry out a penalty match and move to the second round of cards, in which suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the steps is not so clear that this is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to the sports spirit, which is still part of making strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players have not acted to avoid the application of the penalty (this would indeed be a clear case of law fraud), otherwise they have instead chosen the time at which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without overcoming the penalty or running away from it.
Even though the boundary between genius and law fraud is widespread, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy appears to me due to two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way the director transmits them to provoke them.
The harm caused by these actions to the principles of sport is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
