The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicants Service Centers before interviewing in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to apply to the Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC) before interviewing in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be revised by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will provide certain benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The applicant will make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa with application (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for visa for merchants and investors.
Those wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and take their fingerprints.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the $26 extra service fee.
For more information on the new procedure for applying for the visa, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
