A Global Plan to Renew Lighting
The UN yesterday in Cancún proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds to nearly a third of the additional reduction to be achieved to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan follows the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that still monopolise 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by compact fluo bulbs or, better, by light-emitting diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the majority of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be emitted for lighting.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major issuer countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to increase global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will take another 5 Gt from this balance sheet to be able to stabilize the climate rise to 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 in order to avoid it falling out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, produces light.
With compact fluorescent bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is reduced twice as much.
Compact fluorescent bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the possible savings with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These brand-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emitting very little heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several experts have made reserves for compact fluorine bulbs because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, the report says, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluo bulb, but rather the coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year on electricity purchases and eight million tonnes of CO2, equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants that would cost it 2.5 billion dollars to build.
