Avengers and spy hackers in diligence
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it turns out to be an apparent scandal, a scandal that appears as a scandal only in the face of the hypocrisy that governs the relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes at the international level, and prefigures a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed by order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation that every file constituted by a secret service (from any nation) consists exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits are only reporting what could be read for months in any newspaper (except those Berlusconi owns), and Gaddafi’s sinisterly caricatural profile has long been sketch-matter for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret records should be composed of only known news is essential to the dynamics of the intelligence services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous works.
And this not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unprecedented research (nor knows where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only in what they already know, and who reconfirms what they had already learned.
That's the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
I'm going to the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or limited-minded) the head of the secret services (if not he could be, I know, editor at Liberation), who holds as true only what he acknowledges.
The top secret information on Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of states can phone or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have become spy centers.
Any spectator of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put American diplomacy under bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal does not put the victims in crisis as much as the "wurflings".
But let’s come to the deep nature of what happened.
Once upon a time of Orwell, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had proved completely since, being able to control every movement through the phone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the avenger of the citizen – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it falls within the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets to her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has made it too big to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any reserved information online - this would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is in vain to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know well that for the moment my prediction is science fiction and therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence to uncontrollable routes, bearing only messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept as a single copy in closed drawers: at the bottom, the Watergate spy attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now moving forward in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet restored a wired telegraph.
The (analog) videos allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backward and uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to skip from chapter to chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, we go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the travel it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not surprising that the policies and communications techniques relate to horseback riding cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press was trying to figure out what was going on in the secret of the embassies.
The embassies are now asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: How France Disrupts its Financing Promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the delivery of the promises of early-start or early-start financing made by developed countries.
And the big French bidding is revealed.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (420 million a year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU took the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start financing: report detailing the actions of its member states, press conference, large side event, distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation is appreciable and appreciated in its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of accuracy.
The EU has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, under the Copenhagen Agreement, "new and additional" in order to ensure that additional effort is made without being to the detriment of Public Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered the year 2009 as a reference: international financing is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years for fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of public development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or the overall level of Public Development Assistance.
Concretely, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to meet its commitment in terms of “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses their own method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that 1 € loaned is equivalent to 1 € given.
Obviously, this is hardly justifiable: the effort is not comparable.
While the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is given... At the most, it should only be counted under its commitments as the cost of the loan for the lender country (the borrower).
But France has nothing to do with such a reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (otherwise) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 euro to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
Nice passport!
In short, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only €36.1 million, it can make it appear that it spends €420 million "new and additional" in line with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would other Member States continue to give if enough to lend?) and in negotiations since the developing countries are not completely dumb...
The Early Financing Chapter is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to all climate discussions.
But it could be another grain of sand in the immense machine that is UNFCCC.
Hopefully this is not the case.
In any case, lessons learned from this first year of early financing are essential.
First, France could announce a change in its accounting mode for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But most importantly, France could push forward discussions on the long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope therefore lies in the new Minister of the Environment, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would be of nature to increase the level of international trust necessary to advance the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old ingested 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (formerly Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the small number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the issue treated", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and one snack in a day by a child about a ten-year-old, in the supermarkets of Oise and Paris.
These types of meals, including official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as treats, have been examined by laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The record is overwhelming: 81 chemicals of which 42 are classified as potential or likely carcinogens and five are classified as certain carcinogens as well as 37 substances that can act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by several institutions such as the International Centre for Research on Cancer.
“Although, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is concerning,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three proven to be certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues likely to disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemical substances, a fungicide of which is prohibited in France.
The same goes for Kenyan green beans, included in lunch, on which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, chopped steak, canned tuna, and even bread stick and chewing gum were truffled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroforms.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the "richest" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plastic plate used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt from it.
The ultimate risk to the consumer of this “contaminant cocktail” “is likely underestimated,” according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "the urgency of the situation" to impose a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "the increase in diseases of civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
